thread.title: H.S. girls cross-country: Taylor Domico leads Wayne Hills sweep at Big North Independence Division championship

title: H.S. girls cross-country: Taylor Domico leads Wayne Hills sweep at Big North Independence Division championship
text:
MITSU YASUKAWA/STAFF PHOTOGRAPHER Taylor Domico of Wayne Hills finishing first in 20:25 at Big North Independence meet Tuesday. 
Tuesday at Garret Mountain, Wayne Hills became the 11th team to pull off the sweep, taking the top five slots in the Big North Independence meet for a 15-76 win over West Milford in the first of three championship days in the conference. 
“We talked about it before the race that we’d never won with a score of 15 before and we wanted to try and get it,” said Taylor Domico, who won the race by nearly 100 yards with a time of 20:25 over the 5,000-meter course. “We’ve worked hard all year and have pushed the younger kids to work as hard as we do.” 
Domico led teammates Emily Becker, Katerina Zachmann, Natalie Zawistowska and Shea Brennan to finish within 39 seconds of each other as Wayne Hills averaged 20:49.6, a time topped by only 10 Passaic County teams in the history of the course. The Patriots have won the Independence race all six years it’s been run. 
“We have our eyes set on November and some very specific goals,” said coach Jason Staggers. 
“We’ve never won the section and we hope that we can compete with Northern Highlands there.” 
Ironically, the last girls team to throw a shutout in a division meet, Clifton, won the Liberty, 39-42-50 over Passaic Tech and Bergen Tech despite nearly having no one in the top five. 
The Mustangs, who swept the Liberty race in 2010 were led by junior Anisha Khandakar, who finished fifth. Bergen Tech went 1-2 behind race-winner Michelle Kubasek, working her way back from a chronic shin splints problem. 
Fellow senior Abigail McLaughlin who finished only 20 yards behind and then Passaic Tech went 3-4-6 led by Sarah Shannon. But Clifton took the next five spots after Passaic Tech’s third and its gap from 1-6 was only 56 seconds, albeit about a minute slower than Wayne Hills’ 1-5 margin. 
“I’m really proud of this team,” said Clifton coach John Pontes. “This might have been a surprise to some but knowing these girls like I do nothing surprises me. 
“There’s no animosity on this team and they always work together towards a common goal,” said Pontes, whose girls team has won or shared a title in one division or another since 2004. © 2015 North Jersey Media Group Tags:
